<hr class="datasources-hr" />";s:10:"post_title";s:31:"Projections of Future Education";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:31:"projections-of-future-education";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2016-09-11 19:45:16";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2016-09-11 19:45:16";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:3:"192";s:4:"guid";s:39:"http://ourworldindata.org/?page_id=2447";s:10:"menu_order";s:3:"300";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"page";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:5;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:4:"3108";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"2";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-11-17 20:23:01";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-11-17 20:23:01";s:12:"post_content";s:22294:"<p>This entry is concerned with the value change with respect to the materialistic or post-materialistic orientation of individuals and societies as a whole. The definition and measurement will be explained in the "Data Quality &amp; Definition" section below¬†in some detail. Materialists are mostly concerned with material needs and physical and economic security. In contrast to this, post-materialists 'strive for self-actualization, stress the aesthetic and the intellectual, and cherish belonging and esteem' as Held et al (2009) put it.[ref]Held, M., J. M√ºller, F. Deutsch, E. Grzechnik &amp; C. Welzel (2009). ‚ÄúValue Structure and Dimensions. Empirical Evidence from the German World Values Survey.‚Äù World Values Research 2(3):55-76. Online <a href="http://www.worldvaluessurvey.org/wvs/articles/folder_published/paperseries_31/files/WVR_02_03_Held%20et%20al">here</a>.[/ref]</p>
<h2>Empirical View</h2>
<h6>Shift toward post-materialist values among the publics of nine Western societies, 1970 and 2000 ‚Äì Inglehart &amp; Welzel (2005)[ref]</h6>
<p>This is taken from Inglehart and Welzel (2005) - Modernization, Cultural Change, and Democracy: The Human Development Sequence. Cambridge University Press.¬†It is online on Google Books <a href="http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=O4APtKh7JqQC&amp;printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false">here</a>.[/ref]<strong><br />
<a title="" href="http://ourworldindata.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/The-shift-toward-postmaterialist-values-among-the-publics-of-nine-Western-societies-1970-and-2000-Inglehart-and-Welzel-2005.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-3109 size-medium" src="http://ourworldindata.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/The-shift-toward-postmaterialist-values-among-the-publics-of-nine-Western-societies-1970-and-2000-Inglehart-and-Welzel-2005-645x444.png" alt="The shift toward postmaterialist values among the publics of nine Western societies, (1970 and 2000) - Inglehart and Welzel (2005)" width="400" height="275" /></a></strong></p>
<h6>Change in materialist/post-materialist priorities in 5 EU countries, 1970 and 2000 ‚Äì¬†Welzel (2007)[ref]</h6>
<p>This is taken from Christian Welzel (2007) ‚Äì¬†Individual Modernity. Chapter 10 in Dalton &amp; Klingemann: The Oxford Handbook of Political Behaviour. The page proofs are online <a href="http://www.worldvaluessurvey.org/wvs/articles/folder_published/publication_573/files/10-DaltonandKlingemann-chap10.pdf">here</a>.</p>
<p>The authors' note on the source: Data for France, Germany (West), Italy, Belgium, Netherlands (samples equally weighed). Data from 1970 are from Eurobarometer, data for 2000 from World Values Survey 1999‚Äì2001.[/ref]<br />
<strong><a title="" href="http://ourworldindata.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Change-in-Materialist-Postmaterialist-Priorities-in-5-EU-Countries-WVS0.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-3110 size-medium" src="http://ourworldindata.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/Change-in-Materialist-Postmaterialist-Priorities-in-5-EU-Countries-WVS0-586x500.png" alt="Change in Materialist-Postmaterialist Priorities in 5 EU-Countries - WVS0" width="400" height="341" /></a></strong></p>
<h6>Cohort analysis: ¬†share of post-materialists minus the share of materialists in 6 West European societies, 1970-2006 ‚Äì Inglehart (2008)[ref]</h6>
<p>The source is Inglehart (2008) - Changing Values among Western Publics from 1970 to 2006. In West European Politics, 31, 1-2, 130--146.</p>
<p>The paper is online <a href="http://www.worldvaluessurvey.org/wvs/articles/folder_published/publication_559/files/values_1970-2006.pdf">here</a>.</p>
<p>Note by the authors on the data: 'Based on combined weighted sample of Eurobarometer surveys and World Values Surveys in West Germany, France Britain, Italy, the Netherlands and Belgium, in given years, using the four-item materialist/post-materialist values index.'[/ref]<br />
<strong><a title="" href="http://ourworldindata.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/cohort-analysis-the-share-of-post-materialists-minus-the-share-of-materialists-in-6-west-european-societies-1970-2006-inglehart-2008.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-3111 size-medium" src="http://ourworldindata.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/cohort-analysis-the-share-of-post-materialists-minus-the-share-of-materialists-in-6-west-european-societies-1970-2006-inglehart-2008-645x361.png" alt="Cohort Analysis - The share of Post-Materialists minus the share of Materialists in 6 West European Societies, (1970‚Äì2006) ‚Äì Inglehart (2008)" width="400" height="223" /></a></strong></p>
